0.body: Calc: a fully-featured minimalistic calculator built in rust for educational purpose only.
0.title: Calc

1.body:
You can install the latest version from source git clone https://github.com/coco33920/calc
cd calc cargo build --release
./target/release/mini-calc or install it via cargo cargo install mini-calc
1.title: Install

10.body: As of 2.12.2 you can use the calculator without the REPL!
10.title: Non interactive use !

11.body: you use it as a regular calculator
11.title: Usage

12.body: + for the addition - for the subtraction / for the division * for the multiplication ^ for the exponentiation
12.title: Basic Operators

13.body: It's easy to set a variable, just use myvar = value example: myvar = (2+2)
13.title: Setting variable

14.body: pi is pi as a double precision float e is e as a double precision float
14.title: Built-in variable

15.body: The following functions are available Trigonometry sin (vectorized) cos (vectorized) tan (vectorized) Hyperbolic trigonometry sinh (vectorized) cosh (vectorized) tanh (vectorized) Reverse trigonometry asin (vectorized) acos (vectorized) atan (vectorized) Exponentiation exp (vectorized) ln (alias: log) (vectorized) Vectors norm Matrices det invert Plot plot termplot Other sqrt (vectorized) factorial (aliases: fact or !) abs ceil floor round
15.title: Functions

16.body: For trigonometry, the input are assumed to be in radian, if not, you have to put "false" or "true" as second argument, example shown bellow img.png
16.title: Trigonometry

17.body: If you use the exp function you can pass a second argument for the base you are using, if no second arguments are passed this is assumed to be in natural base img.png
17.title: Exp/ln

18.body: You can take the nth root with the sqrt function, by default it takes the second root. img.png
18.title: Root

19.body: You can round to the nth decimal with the round function, by default it round to the integer (floor) img.png
19.title: Round

2.body: You can see how the calculator works over at the usage page
2.title: Usage

20.body: The language supports partial function img.png
20.title: Partial function

21.body: Function has been vectorized, for example
21.title: Vectorization

22.body: You can configure the general color, greeting message, greeting color, prompt and prompt color from the file for example in (for linux) ~/.config/mini-calc/mini-calc.toml Or situated in your operating system config folder.
22.title: Configuration

23.body: The default configuration looks like this img.png
23.breadcrumbs: Config » What the configuration looks like
23.title: What the configuration looks like

24.body: Available colors are purple cyan blue black red yellow green white an hexadecimal colour (ex: "#f7a8d8") Default colour (if the configuration fail to load) is Cyan.
24.title: Colors

25.body: Configuration: img.png It looks like: img.png
25.breadcrumbs: Config » Example of a modified configuration
25.title: Example of a modified configuration

26.body: You can interact and modify the config from the command line the commands are config: show the current config config reload: reload the config config reset: reset the config to default parameters config set categories are : greeting_message greeting_color prompt_color prompt general_color
26.breadcrumbs: Config » Interact in the command line
26.title: Interact in the command line

27.body: You can now use logic! I implemented the following functions: or (alias : ||) and (alias : &&) geq (alias : >=) gt (alias : >) leq (alias : <=) lt (alias :<) eq (alias : ==)
27.title: Logic

29.body: You can plot, backend is provided by GNUPlot, so it should work great on linux and macos but behiaviour on windows is not known.
29.title: Plot

30.body: To display the help just type help
30.title: Help

35.title: Terminal plotting

36.body: The best example to show it is the square function between -5 and 5 with a 0.1 step. The x axis is automatically scaled but not the y axis for now.
36.title: Default

40.body: As of 2.11.0 rational exact math was added, support for Rational operation Rational reduction Was added. It was also added to the stdlibs for the functions.
40.title: Rational exact math

41.body: Or even with inverse of matrices! And it rationalize floats with 10 decimal points of precision (but printed as 5)
